> this? It
> occurs in the following (all in C.ng/bennassuti): inf/14.e, purg/06.e.

These can only be handled by someone with a copy of Bennassuti in hand.
Whenever we find someone, we will need to have the text photocopied or
sent by ILL.  The only other possibility is that it still exists in our
archive at D'mth, and that the copy we sent to England years ago was a
copy of that.  It might be worth checking.  We did Xerox Benn. once....
> 
> 4. Inf/19.e look like it might be truncated. (It did not contain the
> "END OF
> CANTO" message that the other files have.) Please check. Also
> inf/24.e,
> inf/25.e, para/15.e, para/32.e, purg/29.e.

These all seemed OK to me, and I did check them all.
> 
> 5. There are 3 intro.e files and one appendix.e file. How should they
> be
> identified? Perhaps like the similar file in Berthier?

I'm afraid there is no simple answer for all cases.  But there are
answers, as follows:

Inf. intro.  This is an endless discussion, really of Inf. I & II.  But
it is the nucleus of Benn.'s theory of how we must read Dante.  Thus I
think we need to keep it as a proemio to the whole poem, setting it
first.

Purg. intro.  This is not very interesting and can mainly be junked. 
However, starting about 75% of the way along, there are a series of
RETTIFICAZIONI of his earlier comments to various texts in Purg.  I
think we should add them TO EACH COMMENT affected as |Rettificazione
dell'autore.~ at the end of that comment.  Not difficult.  Steve,
"rettificazione" means -- you guessed it -- "rectification."

Purg. appendix.  This is a long discussion of issues raised in his
comment to Purg. I, 75.  It should be added to that note as |Appendice
dell'autore.~  It will make it long, but perhaps more interesting.

Par. intro.  This is a long text, reprinting positive reviews of his
comm. to Inferno.  It has a certain interest, but probably doesn't
belong in the database.
> 
> 6. The last line of para/intro.e looks suspicious. It ends
> "libertini.Z"
